<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Holmgren, 1858" authorityName="Brischke" authorityYear="1880" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Thersilochus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thersilochus (Phradis) brevis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis" subGenus="Phradis">Thersilochus (Phradis) brevis</taxonomicName>
Brischke, 1880.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A moderately large predominantly Holarctic genus with 20 species in the Nearctic region (including two species from Mexico), ca. 40 species in the Palaearctic region, and several species known from Peru, South Africa, and Australia. In Europe, species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Phradis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phradis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phradis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been reared from sap beetle larvae (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Phradis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" family="Nitidulidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Nitidulidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Meligethes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meligethes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Meligethes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.) feeding on rape, but no host record is known for any Nearctic species (
<bibRefCitation author="Horstmann, K" journalOrPublisher="Spixiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="67 - 92" refId="B3" refString="Horstmann, K, 2013a. Revisions of Nearctic Tersilochinae IV. Genus Phradis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae). Spixiana 36 (1): 67 - 92" title="Revisions of Nearctic Tersilochinae IV. Genus Phradis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae)." volume="36" year="2013 a">Horstmann 2013a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Two species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Phradis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phradis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phradis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were known from Mexico until now (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/jhr.63.24491" author="Khalaim, AI" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Hymenoptera Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="61 - 72" refId="B14" refString="Khalaim, AI, Ruiz-Cancino, E, 2018. First record of the genera Diaparsis Foerster and Phradis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae, Tersilochinae) from Mexico. Journal of Hymenoptera Research 63: 61 - 72, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/jhr.63.24491" title="First record of the genera Diaparsis Foerster and Phradis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae, Tersilochinae) from Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/jhr.63.24491" volume="63" year="2018">
Khalaim and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ruíz-Cancino">Ruiz-Cancino</normalizedToken>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
), and the third species, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. belovi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="belovi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. belovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., is described from North Mexico in this paper. The genus is extremely rare in Mexico as all known Mexican species are represented by a single holotype. 
<bibRefCitation author="Horstmann, K" journalOrPublisher="Spixiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="67 - 92" refId="B3" refString="Horstmann, K, 2013a. Revisions of Nearctic Tersilochinae IV. Genus Phradis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae). Spixiana 36 (1): 67 - 92" title="Revisions of Nearctic Tersilochinae IV. Genus Phradis Foerster (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae)." volume="36" year="2013 a">Horstmann (2013a)</bibRefCitation>
in his revision of the Nearctic fauna, also noted that many Nearctic species are rarely collected, and six of 18 revised species (33%) are known from only one specimen. A key to three Mexican species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Phradis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phradis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phradis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is provided below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
